<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="322" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[159,772,489,1155]" box="[159,298,489,515]" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[159,298,489,515]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[159,772,489,1155]" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">
A medium-small species with a forearm length of 
<quantity box="[159,333,557,583]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.595" metricValueMax="5.75" metricValueMin="5.4399999999999995" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="55.95" valueMax="57.5" valueMin="54.4">54.4–57.5 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[351,445,557,583]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[159,172,220,241]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. External measurements (mm) and bacular length (mm) of 14 bat species recently collected at Lekoumou, Congo.Acronyms explained in the Materials and Methods section include means, ranges, and, where relevant, standard deviations. Numbers in parentheses refer to sample size where they differ from those stated in column 2" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" tableUuid="5FAA6645FF93C07DFF03FF23FC6EFEEE">Table 2</tableCitation>
). The face is characterised by a distinctive noseleaf, which includes three vertical processes projecting from the upper part and a fourth smaller vertical process situated at the base of the middle upper process (for further details of the noseleaf morphology see 
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" box="[499,767,725,751]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" refId="ref14301" refString="MONADJEM, A., P. J. TAYLOR, F. P. D. COTTERILL, and M. C. SCHOEMAN. 2010. Bats of Central and Southern Africa: a biogeographic and taxonomic synthesis. WITS University Press, Johannesburg, 596 pp." type="book" year="2010">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[633,683,725,751]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">et al</emphasis>
., 2010
</bibRefCitation>
: Figure 93a and b). The second phalanx of the fourth digit is unique in possessing a transverse spicule of bone, which projects from the outer side of its base for a distance of 
<quantity box="[371,525,860,886]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.5">2.5 to 3 mm</quantity>
into the membrane. The skull (SL: 18.73–20.12) is narrow and elongated with a well developed rostrum. The zygomata are 
<taxonomicName box="[201,238,960,986]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" pageId="10" pageNumber="340" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
outwardly flared but are very greatly expanded dorsally. In the upper dentition, the third molar (M 
<superScript attach="left" box="[195,205,1023,1041]" fontSize="8" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">3</superScript>
) is 
<taxonomicName box="[253,290,1028,1054]" class="Not" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" pageId="10" pageNumber="340" phylum="Myzozoa" rank="class">not</taxonomicName>
reduced, having three commissures and a well developed metacone. The baculum is short (
<quantity box="[168,263,1095,1121]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
); it has a straight shaft with an expanded tip and bilobate base (
<figureCitation box="[381,473,1129,1155]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="9.[816,829,1943,1964]" captionTargetBox="[830,1413,1541,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[816,1430,1523,1932]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIG. 6. Bacula (dorsal view [left] and lateral view [right]) of (A): Hipposideros ruber, HZM.78.40176 and (B): Triaenops afer, HZM.39.40178. Scale = 0.5 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943575" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943575/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="322" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[159,772,1196,1458]" box="[159,356,1196,1222]" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[159,356,1196,1222]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[159,772,1196,1458]" lastBlockId="10.[816,1429,220,517]" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">
The taxon 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1877" box="[322,369,1230,1256]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="afer">
<emphasis box="[322,369,1230,1256]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">afer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is variably treated as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dobson" authorityYear="1871" box="[196,328,1263,1289]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="persicus">
<emphasis box="[196,328,1263,1289]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">T. persicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Simmons" box="[348,543,1263,1289]" firstAuthor="Simmons" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" refId="ref14567" refString="SIMMONS, N. B. 2005. Order Chiroptera. Pp. 312 - 529, in Mammals species of the World (D. E. WILSON and D. M. REEDER, eds). Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, 2142 pp." type="book" year="2005">Simmons, 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Monadjem" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Monadjem" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" refId="ref14301" refString="MONADJEM, A., P. J. TAYLOR, F. P. D. COTTERILL, and M. C. SCHOEMAN. 2010. Bats of Central and Southern Africa: a biogeographic and taxonomic synthesis. WITS University Press, Johannesburg, 596 pp." type="book" year="2010">
Monadjem 
<emphasis box="[700,757,1263,1289]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">et al</emphasis>
., 2010
</bibRefCitation>
) or as a distinct species (
<bibRefCitation author="Happold and Happold" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" refId="ref13898" refString="HAPPOLD, M., and D. C. D. HAPPOLD (eds.). 2013. Mammals of Africa Volume IV: Hedgehogs, shrews, and bats. Bloomsbury Publishing, London, 800 pp." type="book" year="2013">Happold and Happold, 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Benda and Vallo" box="[358,637,1331,1357]" firstAuthor="Benda" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" pagination="1 - 45" refId="ref13068" refString="BENDA, P., and P. VALLO. 2009. Taxonomic revision of the genus Triaenops (Chiroptera: Hipposideridae) with description of a new species from southern Arabia and definitions of a new genus and tribe. Folia Zoologica, 58 (Monograph 1): 1 - 45." type="journal article" year="2009">Benda and Vallo (2009)</bibRefCitation>
considered it to be a discrete species confined to Africa based on differences in the skull, baculum and Cytochrome 
<emphasis box="[264,279,1432,1458]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">b</emphasis>
. Specimens previously collected from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[925,1003,220,246]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Congo</collectingCountry>
were described as a new subspecies 
<emphasis box="[816,948,254,280]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">majusculus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Aellen and Brosset" box="[954,1251,254,280]" firstAuthor="Aellen" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" pagination="435 - 458" refId="ref12825" refString="AELLEN, V., and A. BROSSET. 1968. Chiropteres du sud du Congo (Brazzaville). Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 75: 435 - 458." type="journal article" year="1968">Aellen and Brosset, 1968</bibRefCitation>
on the basis of their large size; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cotterill" box="[1010,1195,288,314]" firstAuthor="Cotterill" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" pagination="187 - 198" refId="ref13656" refString="COTTERILL, F. P. D. 2001. New distribution records of leaf-nosed bats (Microchiroptera: Hipposideridae) in Zimbabwe. Arnoldia Zimbabwe, 10: 187 - 198." type="journal article" year="2001">Cotterill (2001)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">majusculus</emphasis>
may prove to be a distinct species but this is contrary to 
<bibRefCitation author="Benda and Vallo" box="[983,1269,355,381]" firstAuthor="Benda" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" pagination="1 - 45" refId="ref13068" refString="BENDA, P., and P. VALLO. 2009. Taxonomic revision of the genus Triaenops (Chiroptera: Hipposideridae) with description of a new species from southern Arabia and definitions of a new genus and tribe. Folia Zoologica, 58 (Monograph 1): 1 - 45." type="journal article" year="2009">Benda and Vallo (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, who considered even its subspecific status to be questionable. The three specimens from Lekoumou are referred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Aellen &amp; Brosset" authorityYear="1968" box="[851,1076,457,483]" class="Mammalia" family="Hipposideridae" genus="Triaenops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="322" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="afer" subSpecies="majusculus">
<emphasis box="[851,1076,457,483]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">T. afer majusculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being comparable in size to specimens previously collected from 
<collectingCountry box="[1258,1340,491,517]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="10" pageNumber="322">Congo</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
